              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24337585#p24337585" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">dferrantino</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24337445#p24337445" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">rigeek</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Wow .. so I came to the conclusion yesterday that bottling blows and I'm going to start putting together a basic kegging setup sooner than later.  I bottled one batch (48 bottles) and between soaking the bottles, removing the labels, rinsing, and sanitizing, filling and capping, it was literally an all day event.. and only half the bottles needed the labels removed.  Ugh.  But the sample I tasted out of the hydrometer tasted good prior to adding the cherry extract, so I have high hopes for the beer.  Brewed again today, a very simple American Amber Ale.. extract with some steeping grains, 1oz cascade hops, 1oz Mount Hood.  Should ferment out quick and be ready soon... hoping 2-3 weeks.</div><br />Taking the labels off is the biggest pain in the ass of the whole process, you should just do it beforehand.</div><br /><br />Yeah I've decided that whenever I buy bottled beer from now on, as soon as I finish the 6 pack I'll soak them, remove the labels and soak in PBW .. that way all I need to do on bottling day is sanitize them.  That will save a lot of time.

              

              
              
            </div>
