              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24339551#p24339551" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Big Wooly Mammoth</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24337585#p24337585" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">dferrantino</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24337445#p24337445" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">rigeek</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Wow .. so I came to the conclusion yesterday that bottling blows and I'm going to start putting together a basic kegging setup sooner than later.  I bottled one batch (48 bottles) and between soaking the bottles, removing the labels, rinsing, and sanitizing, filling and capping, it was literally an all day event.. and only half the bottles needed the labels removed.  Ugh.  But the sample I tasted out of the hydrometer tasted good prior to adding the cherry extract, so I have high hopes for the beer.  Brewed again today, a very simple American Amber Ale.. extract with some steeping grains, 1oz cascade hops, 1oz Mount Hood.  Should ferment out quick and be ready soon... hoping 2-3 weeks.</div><br />Taking the labels off is the biggest pain in the ass of the whole process, you should just do it beforehand.</div><br /><br /><br />Most labels come off easily with a water and baking soda solution.<br />Do that ahead of time and the rest is dead simple. We've gotten to the point where we can sanitize and fill 40 or so bottles in around 1.5 hours. Half of that time is reserved for letting the bottles mostly dry on the bottle rack.</div><br /><br />Yeah but filling a keg takes ~5 minutes. Even with sanitizing it's a huge time saver if you've got space for the equipment. Plus you can carb more quickly as well as more consistently.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
