        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Well, after about 2 weeks in primary, about 3 weeks in secondary, and 2 months bottle conditioning, I tried my first bottle of <a href="http://www.northernbrewer.com/documentation/allgrain/AG-BieredeGarde.pdf" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Biere de Garde</a>.  I actually modified that recipe slightly since I used left-over hops from previous batches (since it was only bittering hops, I just made sure I matched the alpha levels), and I used 1007 (German Ale) instead of 2112 (California Common) yeast.<br /><br />It turned out a deep golden color, perhaps 14-15 SRM.  Pretty clear considering I didn't use any Irish Moss.  Very mild aroma, pretty smooth.  I can't tell yet whether the flavor is best described as &quot;subtle&quot; or just very, very clean.  Since I sanitized everything, I probably won't get any of the traditional mustiness of a Biere de Garde, but I think I did end up with a good summer time beer.  Now if only the weather were warmer...

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
