          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              So here's a question for you guys regarding taking gravity readings... I'm currently using buckets for fermentation.  In order to take a gravity reading I'd have to take the lid off the bucket, and I assume the CO2 in the headspace would go away and introduce oxygen into the mix. My thief won't fit through the airlock grommet.  Am I harming the beer if I remove the lid 2-3 days in a row to take readings?  Assuming the fermentation is almost stopped, I assume the yeast won't produce enough CO2 to purge the headspace in the bucket of oxygen.  Normally I'd just err on the side of caution and let the fermentation go an extra week, but I'm going to be in a situation where I need to either bottle a batch this coming Sunday, or wait 2 more weeks, and I don't want to do that if I can help it.  Wouldn't be the end of the world, so if taking the lid off to take a reading is that risky I'll just wait it out.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
